reviews.reviewDate: Reviewed in the United States on November 8, 2023
reviews.reviewTitle: 5.0 out of 5 stars Great motherboard at a fantastic price
reviews.reviewText: I used this in my first PC build that was designed for graphics intensive VR gaming, and this motherboard is more than what I need. The only problem I had was that shortly after the build was complete, I ran into a boot error (I cannot remember what that error was or what caused it); all I had to do was uncheck a setting in BIOS, and I've never had a problem since. I will say that I have not experimented with many BIOS settings nor the overclocking features, so I can't vouch for all that. However, given the features and components that it has, you cannot beat this motherboard for the price. Would buy again.

reviews.reviewDate: Reviewed in the United States on January 14, 2024
reviews.reviewTitle: 4.0 out of 5 stars No status LEDs.
reviews.reviewText: i7-13700KF;Asus GeForce GTX 1650 OCCORSAIR VENGEANCE RGB DDR5 2x 16GB CMH32GX5M2E6000C36Dracaena 240 mm AIOSamsung 980 Pro 1TB NVMEThermaltake Toughpower Grand RGB 650W 80+ GoldCooler Master Q300L V2 mATX TowerNew build with new components except the Samsung 980 ProNo display even though system is receiving power and fans and RGB work.Graphics card works in a B550i Aorus Pro AX system.Cleared CMOS and replaced the battery but still nothing.Executed a BIOS upgrade using the Q-Flash Plus but still nothing. the Q-Flash button is inside and not on the back plate.Tried single memory stick in A2 as per manual but still nothing.Attached a speaker to mobo but no sound.This board does not have status LEDs so unable to ascertain where's the hang up. this is a real unfortunate omission since as the 1.2 and later version have this feature according to the manual.Other observation:- the heatsink for the M2A_CPU SSD is tricky to install.- the Q-Flash Plus button and LED are on the board and not next to the USB port on the backplate this is unlike other Aorus boards- no status LEDsWill try some more troubleshooting before requesting RMA. Don't want to purchase a different memory but may have to...Update...The Thermaltake PSU was the culprit. Although, the onboard LED on the graphics card would light, I failed to recognize that the fan was not spinning. The PCIe ports on the modular PSU did not work. Used an Apevia Premier 650W semi-modular and everything worked immediately. The status LEDs may have helped. This happened once I switched to a Gigabyte GTX 1650 graphics card which does not have an onboard LED.Conclusion: make sure that all components are receiving power. even brand new PSU can be partially defective out of the box. I made sure to try different cables and both ports on the PSU before deciding that the PSU was the culprit.
